My goodness! Here I thought my 4090 was power hungry. 
As a recommendation and suggestion, invest in a 1500w UPS. I have one from cyber power.

Do you have a screen that runs at 1000HZ if no then what is the point of 1000 FPS...

Like i get it you want all settings on ultimate capped out crazy style but think about it after you play the game for like say 100 hours you don't really notice the high quality graphics hell in most multiplayer competitive games people turn off shadows and other distractions because its a downgrade in gaming.

comments.text: Haven't really finished the video. The problem with the 5090 is that most of the frames will be generated by AI. It is good, right? Well, in single-player games that revolve around YOUR hardware and YOUR software, it is a massive spike in performance for most games when you talk about smoothness of the game. Now, for any MP game that relies on constant data from your computer and is reliant mostly on the server getting the data and sending you the data, it doesn't affect anything. If your software, on your PC generates additional 3 frames between the in-game frames, the server just DOESNT CARE. It will still utilize only the frames between the ones you generated. It doesn't care, it won't use and your visual smoothness is exactly that, - visual smoothness. They haven't actually increased performance, they added fake frames between the real frames, which doesn't equal performance in any way. And it is useful only in SP games that do not rely on client-server interaction. The servers won't use your fake frames and they don't care.

comments.text:
No, it does not break the laws of physics. A 600W GPU can produce less heat than a 400W GPU if it is more efficient in converting electrical power into useful work (such as rendering frames) rather than waste heat.

How Is This Possible?

Higher Efficiency Components

Newer GPUs use advanced silicon fabrication processes (e.g., smaller nanometer nodes like 3nm or 5nm).

These processes improve power efficiency, meaning more energy is used for computation rather than heat dissipation.

Better Power Delivery & VRMs

Higher-quality voltage regulation modules (VRMs) and power management techniques reduce wasted energy in conversion.

Advanced Cooling Solutions

Vapor chamber cooling, better heatsinks, and fans can dissipate heat more effectively.

This means even if total power consumption is higher, the GPU surface feels cooler due to better heat dissipation.

Dynamic Power Management

Modern GPUs optimize power usage dynamically, consuming only what is needed per workload, reducing unnecessary heat generation.

Example:

A 400W GPU with 75% efficiency wastes 100W as heat (400W × 25%).

A 600W GPU with 90% efficiency wastes 60W as heat (600W × 10%).

Even though the 600W GPU draws more power, it generates less heat overall because it converts more of that power into useful work rather than waste heat.

The frame gen comparison is extraordinarily misleading. You will have similar input delay to max native no frame gen but thats not the comparison to be had. Max Ultra settings vs lowest settings and lower resolution creates a drastically lower input delay and increased responsiveness. Thats the distinction. You might as well tape a post it note with 10,000 fps on it because if you don't have this 5090 which will never just be "only 2,000" dollars you are gonna be playing with the input delay of 20-60 fps while it "looks" like 200+. comments.text: I want to clarify for everyone: the main issue with fake 240 FPS isn’t visual artifacts, but latency. When paid-off reviewers like this one are confronted about it, they dismissively say, 'But the latency doesn’t increase!' — as if they don’t understand that 240 FPS should come with a latency of around 4-5 milliseconds, not 30 ms. With such massive delay, it’ll feel like you’re playing at 30 FPS, even though the counter claims 240. And let’s not forget the 1% lows — they don’t improve, so you’ll still experience annoying microstutters that ruin the experience. Don’t fall for this nonsense.

comments.text:
It' really simple. None of the frames discussed are fake.
"Frame Gen" is just marketing fluff for motion interpolation between rendered source frames.
Frames Per Second / Frame Time conventionally was used a metric to indicate the "responsiveness" of the rendering of realtime graphics. If you mix motion interpolation frames into that metric it doesn't convey the same meaning anymore.
The sensation of having a higher fps and direct correlation to how responsive the game feels is no longer 1:1.
Frame interpolation has been a thing for videos for a long time but you won't see blockbuster movies advertising a 240fps cinema experience because the movie was shot at 24fps and your interpolated 9 additional frames in between (that will have artefacts). It would come across as a tacky post-processing effect, because it is.

comments.text:
When Nvidia is chalking out a new product range, there is a maximum die size that they can produce cost effectively at scale. Assuming Moore's law is mostly trucking along, it's around 600mm2 and 40% faster than last gen. For this example, lets say a new generation die is 600mm2 and has 10,000 cores and is given the nomenclature EX-102 (102 notates that highest end non data center silicon)

The tradition would then follow that their Titan and Quadro cards would get 95%-100% of the number of cores that this full 102 die has to offer (because they are using this die). So in this example they would have 10,000 cores.

The 80ti - Also on a 102 - 93% of the 10,000 cores, so around 9300 cores.

The 80 - 102/103 - 66-80% of the 102's full cores. But here's the thing. Sometimes these end up on 103. A smaller, cheaper, die. The other skus up until this point have fused off sections of the 102 die. The 103 is a different piece of silicon entirely. While it might seem unfair to compare them, they are still the same in architecture and scale linearly in some workloads. In any case, we would expect 66% of the cores or in this example 6600 cuda cores.

The 70 class cards are normally 50% and built on 104 so 5000 cores

The 60 class on 106 and hovers around the low 30s or 3000 cores

-----------------------------------------------

This is the expectation as it has been set for the better part of 15 years. It has only been until last gen [4000 series] that we received cards that were substantially different.

The last 90 sku was 87% of the full 102 die. Substantially less than a normal 80ti or titan but curiously, significantly more money. The 80ti, which used to give you the most silicon for the money (again around 90%) is now gone and replaced with the 4080 super, which was 55%. A noticeable drop in the amount of silicon. The standard 4080 even worse at 52%. The 4070 is a shocking 32%.

Using the data I've listed above, it is clear to see that Nvidia has merely moved their entire stack down to make room for their 90 class cards. Again... these 90 cards have no substantial architecture differences that justifies the creation of a new sku. They aren't substantially more silicon. No HBM. No MCM. No stacked cache. They are just an 80ti class with 2-3gb vram modules soldered on. Is that worth $1500-$2000? Maybe... But what I cannot abide by is the squashing of the rest of their product stack to make it look like a better value than it really is.

Now we have the release of the 50 series.

5090 - 102 - 88% of 102 cores
5080 - 103 - 45%
5070 - 104 - 31 %

Are you seeing the downward pattern here? In two generations we have seen 80 class cards go from 80% of all the possible cores (3000 series) to 45% and increase from $699 to $999. Even adjusted for inflation, there is a massive markup on this.

I've really gone on long enough and bless you to anyone who has taken the time to read this.

The one missing but obvious comparison between nvidia GPU generations is the foundry nm in which they were made. 5090 is still on 4nm, just like 4090 was, this is why improvements are much more reserved and power efficiency is completely absent. Frame generation is actually the path forward as moore's law slows down.

980TI - 28nm
1080TI - 16nm
2080TI - 12nm
3090 - 8nm
4090 - 4nm (or 5nm depending who's counting, but, TSMC N4)
5090 - 4nm (TSMC N4 enhanced)

comments.text: The ComputerBase review provided more insight into the power efficiency curve of the 5090 vs the 4090 at 4K. When they are both limited to 450W, the 5090 is 17% faster, versus the 24% that was measured at the full 575W. At 400W, the 5090 is around 12% faster than the stock 4090. However, this analysis has the caveat that it's rare for the 4090 to pull the entire available 450W (as evidenced by the fact that it only loses a mere 2% on average at 350W vs 450W), so it's not perfectly apples-to-apples. Though, the 5090 is clearly capable of doing slightly more with the same power budget (at least at reasonable power limits) compared to the 4090, but still not a terribly impressive generational uplift.

comments.text: Honestly, three out of the four frames are AI generated. They are not "real" frames. If you want to find the real framerate, divide the FPS by four. Let's use 175 FPS. Dividing by four gives us 43.75, so we will round up to 44. Those are the actual rendered frames. Now, multiply 44 by three, which gives us 132. That's the number of AI frames. The generated frames seem like a scam that hides the real FPS and performance from the customer. With AI doing all this work, latency goes up and makes it actually slower to respond to inputs.

comments.text:
I know my comment is a bit long-winded, but I just had to share my thoughts on this.

With all this AI-based generation and prediction, I can't help but worry that when the RTX 7090 or 8090 comes out, it might be nothing more than a wireless chip paired with a subscription service. Imagine frames being generated at Nvidia HQ and sent to you remotely. You’d have to sell an arm and a leg for the chip, a kidney for the subscription, and, of course, hand over your personal data for AI prediction training. All this just to track your every move using predictive algorithms to anticipate your behavior before you’ve even made plans for the next week.

Now, don’t get me wrong—AI has incredible potential in fields like medicine, technology, and engineering. But in my opinion, AI-FPS generation feels like a step too far. Do we really need AI guessing, ‘Oh! I think this is how the next four frames will look’? There’s a meaningful difference between true, calculated frame rates (our ‘lovable math nerd’ GPUs) and the AI-generated ‘respectable-guessing-game’ frame rates. Instead, I believe big corporations like AMD, Nvidia, MSI, Intel, Apple, and Samsung should focus their efforts on improving computational capabilities in general.

Hear me out: why not direct that innovation toward something like quantum computing? I know it sounds far-fetched, but all I want is for my GPU to be the graphics-processing calculator it was meant to be—not a device that says, “Oh, you’re only getting 60 FPS? Let our AI guess the next 180 FPS for you. :)”
Maybe the solution could involve separating tasks, like having one processor focus on ray tracing while another handles the rest of the textures instead of this AI guessing game.

On top of that, some games are launching with poor optimization, and I think developers should work on addressing these issues. For example, lowering the nanite count in some titles could significantly improve performance. This insight comes from Threat Interactive, who discusses these challenges in videos like:

"Fake Optimization in Modern Graphics (And How We Hope To Save It)"
"Challenged To 3X FPS Without Upscaling in UE5 | Insults From Toxic Devs Addressed"

Now, I’m not trying to berate game developers for “doing a poor job in optimizing game textures and light ray-tracing.” I understand game development is incredibly complex, and balancing innovation with performance is no small feat. It’s just that the evidence presented by Threat Interactive is compelling to me, and it highlights areas where optimization could make a significant difference.

As a failing 12th grader, and someone whose only realistic option for a job is military service, I can’t really say much on the topic of “game devs doing a poor job in optimizing games” I’m just a kid who plays Minecraft on an MSI GP70 2PE Leopard (a used, almost 11-year-old laptop). But someday, I want to get into animation and animate my HFY story after I (hopefully) save up enough money for a high-end PC following my mandatory service.

comments.text: It’s a 3ms penalty in comparison to the base frame rate without frame gen. comments.text: I really don’t understand all the hate for the use of AI, it’s quite literally the future and nvidia is getting a head-start.  Clearly for competitive games where frames and latency matters, it’s not worth using AI upscaling. But the results make it clear that a couple of artifacts and more latency is actually worth the trade off depending on the game. Yes, it is unfortunate that we are not getting more raw performance, but how could we possibly expect nvidia to shove an additional 30% performance every year while still having the same thermal capacity and somewhat similar cost. It’s quite literally impossible for nvidia to deliver that same jump in performance every year without bumping up the costs and we need to realize that. The use of AI is what we shape it to be, we will now be expected to pay for how nvidia decides to use AI in combination with their architecture. As far as I know, nvidia is the only company to offer path tracing with this level of frame rate. If artifacts and framerate is that big of an issue then tone it down to 2X

comments.text:
Nothing about this is impressive at all. The native performance increases are completely inline (or worse) than expected for the increased power draw and price increase. Any variance in performance increase across games just comes down to drivers. The cooler is smaller, and of course worse than 4090.  All the frame gen artifacts are exactly the same stuff you see when doing offline frame gen rendering from algorithms that are 20+ years old. I just don't see the point of looking at a game at 4x the FPS when you still have the same latency as 30fps. 

Of course the latency doesn't get worse, you are looking at the native FPS with realtime frame interpolation. The entire point of higher FPS is less latency, less input lag, less felt latency. With frame gen you get none of that.

ARM SoCs are going to absolutely eat this giant power hungry GPU concept for lunch over the next couple of years. What Nvidia has been doing recently very much feels like when Intel ran out of ideas and just kept increasing the clock speeds.

comments.text:
I do understand the preference for a lower native framerate with no framegen, because it's like the preference for zero TAA or motion blur.  I personally appreciate a little motion blur, because it can hide the choppiness of a lower framerate (<90fps), and I think it makes motion on a screen look more like real life.  I also think TAA is great because I am very sensitive to specular aliasing.  But PC gaming is all about tailoring the experience to your tastes right?  You want to play games with no framegen, no motion blur, and injected SMAA, go for it.  That's your preference.

I also bet the way framegen looks really depends on the pixel response time of your monitor.  Like how much framegen blurs the image by outrunning your pixels at your monitor's maximum refresh rate - I know we don't all have OLED screens.  (I've chosen to use my cheaper VA monitor at 120Hz instead of 165Hz, because of the black-level smearing (pixel response isn't able to keep up at 6ms per frame, but it does okay at 8.33ms per frame.)

As far as the fake frames argument, I don't see how it's different than all the other game engine techniques used to trick your eyes/brain into thinking what you're seeing is real.  As long as the image I'm seeing is acceptable to my brain, and the controls aren't sluggish to the point it annoys me, I don't care what software technique is rendering that image.  I am over the moon that with a slightly-outdated $1000 PC I can play brand-new games with great image quality, good responsiveness, and smooth as butter.

comments.text:
So here is the deal with "frame generation", it's a marketing term... What you're seeing is called frame interpolation, and its old tech. What's new is that we have an AI model generating the frames in-between frames, that's it. What you're seeing is delayed frames. Two frames that are generated by the game and in-between the two we generate filler frames. You won't see any increase in delay because you're still seeing the same two frames. Only thing you get is the mushy fake frames and it becomes a little more jarring than the original two frames when you see them...

Good for single player games bad for any live games

comments.text: Nah, you won't be pushing the cards anywhere near what these people are. These are artificial tests done in clean testing environments to see theoretical maximums. These aren't practical results. If you're really curious next time your in game, check your power usage, then compare it to benchmarks off GN or LTT or anywhere really and the power draw figures they provide won't be anything near actual practical use. And if power is really a concern. There's a really easy fix: Cap your FPS rate. If you like to play at 120, then cap it at 120, if you like to play at 240, then cap at 240. Those extra frames, even if you're only shaving off 10 can be the difference between a card pulling max load and one that's sipping.

They just threw 30% more CUDA cores on there so that it technically also is better in terms of raw rasterization, but of course that means it uses about that much more power. Gamers need to accept that Nvidia cannot violate the laws of physics and so they have no choice but to seek performance gains in other ways, and the uplifts caused by DLSS and framegen should be taken more seriously. In the future, we will have to judge the cards on how they improve these technologies, reducing artifacts, reducing latency, etc, rather than raw rasterization improvements.
